Anthony,

We are hoping to make the HyperNEAT Users=
 Page at http://eplex.cs.ucf.edu/hyperNEATpage/HyperNEAT.html into a place =
where people can have questions like yours answered. The &quot;Introduction / Wh=
at is HyperNEAT?&quot; section on that page is intended to provide some general =
answers to beginners without having to read a research paper. Did that sect=
ion help you at all? I&#39;d like to make the page as useful as possible and we=
 will continue to improve it.

To answer your question, HyperNEAT is a sign=
ificant step beyond NEAT so it involves a lot of new ideas that aren&#39;t part=
 of the original NEAT. Some of those concepts can theoretically be applied =
on top of non-NEAT methods. For example, in the following paper, NEAT is su=
bstituted with GP to create a &quot;HyperGP,&quot; in which GP evolves the CPPN:

Buk=
 Z., Koutn=EDk J., =A9norek M., NEAT in HyperNEAT Substituted with Genetic =
Programming, In: ICANNGA 2009. 
http://cig.felk.cvut.cz/research/publicatio=
ns/hypergp.pdf

That said, HyperNEAT addresses a limitation of NEAT, which =
is a limitation of all direct encodings: In NEAT, there is one gene for eve=
ry connection in the network. Even with complexification, that kind of repr=
esentation cannot hope to scale to networks with millions or more connectio=
ns, because such networks would have millions or more genes, which is an as=
tronomical search space. 

However, there are in fact 100 trillion connecti=
ons in the human brain, which means that in principle it is possible to evo=
lve such structures. Yet there are only about 30,000 genes in the human gen=
ome, which suggests that any evolutionary approach to evolving large-scale =
neural networks must encode the connection weights in a compressed descript=
ion, which is called an indirect encoding.

In HyperNEAT, the indirect enco=
ding is the CPPN, which encodes the connectivity of a network as a pattern =
across its geometry. HyperNEAT combines the idea of indirect encoding with =
a strong notion of geometry and builds on our understanding of encoding pat=
terns to produce an algorithm that encodes large-scale topographies (i.e. c=
onnection weights across a geometry). Thus it extends NEAT by giving it the=
 power of indirect encoding, thereby greatly expanding the scope of network=
s it can evolve.

Of course NEAT is still there under the hood. NEAT is evo=
lving the CPPNs, which in turn encode neural networks (called substrates in=
 HyperNEAT). The CPPNs themselves are still complexifying. However, that co=
mplexification is no longer literally adding one connection at a time to a =
neural network. Rather it is adding *information* to the encoding, so that =
it can encode more complex *holistic* connectivity patterns. In other words=
, HyperNEAT means that evolution is no longer limited by the dimensionality=
 of the inputs and outputs but rather can search for the correct implicit p=
roblem complexity, whatever that may be, inside the CPPN. The substrate (wh=
ich the CPPN encodes) will then have as many connections as it needs, in pr=
inciple up to millions or even trillions (with enough CPU power).

It is tr=
ue that geometry may be vague or difficult to decide in some problems. Thos=
e may be more difficult for users to approach with HyperNEAT. Yet I think m=
ost if not all problems can ultimately be posed within some geometry, even =
if it is abstract or conceptual. As Jeff Clune has shown (https://www.msu.e=
du/~jclune/webfiles/publications/Clune-HyperNEATSensitivityToGeometry.pdf),=
 geometry does not need to be perfect, or necessarily even close to perfect=
, for HyperNEAT to still find some regularities to exploit, so while it may=
 be an imperfect art, geometry is still ultimately a useful tool for convey=
ing exploitable information about a domain.

I hope that provides some insi=
ght,

ken

