ake the page as useful as
possible and we will continue to improve it.&lt;br&gt;
=
&lt;br&gt;
To answer your question, HyperNEAT is a significant step beyond NEAT s=
o it
involves a lot of new ideas that aren&#39;t part of the original NEAT. Som=
e of
those concepts can theoretically be applied on top of non-NEAT methods=
. For
example, in the following paper, NEAT is substituted with GP to creat=
e a
&quot;HyperGP,&quot; in which GP evolves the CPPN:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Buk Z., Kou=
tn=EDk J., =A9norek M., NEAT in HyperNEAT Substituted with Genetic
Programm=
ing, In: ICANNGA 2009. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;a href=3D&quot;http://cig.felk.cvut.cz/research/pub=
lications/hypergp.pdf&quot;&gt;http://cig.felk.cvut.cz/research/publications/hyperg=
p.pdf&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
That said, HyperNEAT addresses a limitation of NEAT, whi=
ch is a limitation of
all direct encodings: In NEAT, there is one gene for =
every connection in the
network. Even with complexification, that kind of r=
epresentation cannot hope to
scale to networks with millions or more connec=
tions, because such networks
would have millions or more genes, which is an=
 astronomical search space. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
However, there are in fact 100 trilli=
on connections in the human brain, which
means that in principle it is poss=
ible to evolve such structures. Yet there are
only about 30,000 genes in th=
e human genome, which suggests that any
evolutionary approach to evolving l=
arge-scale neural networks must encode the
connection weights in a compress=
ed description, which is called an indirect
encoding.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
In HyperNEAT=
, the indirect encoding is the CPPN, which encodes the connectivity
of a ne=
twork as a pattern across its geometry. HyperNEAT combines the idea of indi=
rect
encoding with a strong notion of geometry and builds on our understand=
ing of
encoding patterns to produce an algorithm that encodes large-scale t=
opographies
(i.e. connection weights across a geometry). Thus it extends NE=
AT by giving it
the power of indirect encoding, thereby greatly expanding t=
he scope of networks
it can evolve.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Of course NEAT is still there =
under the hood. NEAT is evolving the CPPNs, which
in turn encode neural net=
works (called substrates in HyperNEAT). The CPPNs
themselves are still comp=
lexifying. However, that complexification is no longer
literally adding one=
 connection at a time to a neural network. Rather it is
adding *information=
* to the encoding, so that it can encode more complex
*holistic* connectivi=
ty patterns. In other words, HyperNEAT means that
evolution is no longer li=
mited by the dimensionality of the inputs and outputs
but rather can search=
 for the correct implicit problem complexity, whatever
that may be, inside =
the CPPN. The substrate (which the CPPN encodes) will then
have as many con=
nections as it needs, in principle up to millions or even
trillions (with e=
nough CPU power).&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
It is true that geometry may be vague or difficu=
lt to decide in some problems.
Those may be more difficult for users to app=
roach with HyperNEAT. Yet I think
most if not all problems can ultimately b=
e posed within some geometry, even if
it is abstract or conceptual. As Jeff=
 Clune has shown (&lt;a
href=3D&quot;https://www.msu.edu/~jclune/webfiles/publicati=
ons/Clune-HyperNEATSensitivityToGeometry.pdf&quot;&gt;https://www.msu.edu/~jclune/w=
ebfiles/publications/Clune-HyperNEATSensitivityToGeometry.pdf&lt;/a&gt;),
geometr=
y does not need to be perfect, or necessarily even close to perfect, for
Hy=
perNEAT to still find some regularities to exploit, so while it may be an
i=
mperfect art, geometry is still ultimately a useful tool for conveying
expl=
oitable information about a domain.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
I hope that provides some insi=
ght,&lt;br&gt;
